window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["chronic-coronary-disease"]={"slug": "chronic-coronary-disease", "title": "Chronic Coronary Disease", "tagline": "An ISCHEMIA-era framework for chronic coronary disease: pretest probability, functional versus anatomic testing, the medical-therapy-first paradigm, a practical antianginal and antithrombotic formulary (including intravenous cangrelor), and SYNTAX/FREEDOM-guided revascularization, aligned to the 2023 AHA/ACC Chronic Coronary Disease guideline.", "level": 1, "readMin": 46, "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning Objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This module moves you from resident-level recognition of stable angina to first-year-fellow command of chronic coronary disease (CCD) in the era defined by the ISCHEMIA trial and the 2023 AHA/ACC/ACCP/ASPC/NLA/PCNA Chronic Coronary Disease guideline. The organizing insight of the modern framework is that in most patients with stable CCD, optimal medical therapy is the foundation and revascularization is layered on to relieve refractory symptoms or to treat high-risk anatomy, not to reflexively 'fix' an angiographic stenosis."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Define chronic coronary disease and place it within the current nomenclature (stable ischemic heart disease, chronic coronary syndrome, INOCA/ANOCA).", "Estimate pretest probability of obstructive CAD and select functional versus anatomic testing rationally, including coronary CT angiography with FFR-CT.", "Apply the ISCHEMIA-trial framework: what routine invasive management does and does not add over guideline-directed medical therapy.", "Prescribe antianginal therapy fluently — beta-blockers, calcium channel blockers, nitrates, and ranolazine — with starting and target doses, contraindications, and monitoring.", "Build a contemporary antithrombotic and secondary-prevention regimen, including the specific scenarios, dosing, and transitions for intravenous cangrelor.", "Make revascularization decisions using anatomic complexity (SYNTAX), diabetic status (FREEDOM), and physiologic lesion assessment (FFR/iFR)."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The fellow-level pivot: stop asking 'is there a stenosis?' and start asking 'does this patient have a high-risk substrate (left main, multivessel disease with diabetes, reduced ejection fraction) or refractory symptoms despite maximal medical therapy?' Those two questions — not the mere presence of a lesion — drive the catheterization laboratory."}]}, {"id": "definitions", "title": "Definitions and Nomenclature", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Chronic coronary disease is the umbrella term adopted by the 2023 AHA/ACC guideline for the broad population of patients with established or suspected atherosclerotic coronary disease in a stable phase — outside the acute coronary syndrome window. It deliberately replaces the older, activity-centric term stable ischemic heart disease to emphasize that atherosclerosis is a lifelong, biologically active process even when symptoms are quiescent."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Chronic coronary disease (CCD)", "def": "Patients with stable, non-acute coronary atherosclerosis: those after MI or revascularization, those with stable angina or an anginal equivalent, those with vasospastic or microvascular angina, and asymptomatic patients with documented obstructive CAD."}, {"term": "Chronic coronary syndrome (CCS)", "def": "The parallel ESC term (2019, updated 2024). Reframes CAD as a dynamic disease that alternates between stable and unstable phases, making the point that a 'stable' label is a phase, not a cure."}, {"term": "INOCA / ANOCA", "def": "Ischemia (or Angina) with No Obstructive Coronary Arteries — anginal symptoms and objective ischemia without an epicardial stenosis >=50%. Encompasses coronary microvascular dysfunction and vasospastic (Prinzmetal) angina; disproportionately affects women and is frequently dismissed as noncardiac."}, {"term": "Silent ischemia", "def": "Objective myocardial ischemia without angina, common in diabetes and the elderly; carries prognostic weight comparable to symptomatic ischemia."}, {"term": "Ischemic cardiomyopathy", "def": "LV systolic dysfunction (EF <=40%) attributable to CAD, whether from prior infarction or chronic hibernation; a distinct high-risk CCD phenotype that changes revascularization calculus (STICH)."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — the CCD population is not one disease. Remember 'the five stable faces': Post-MI, Post-revascularization, Stable angina, Vasospastic/microvascular, and Silent/asymptomatic obstructive. Each carries a different testing and treatment emphasis even though all share the CCD label."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The nomenclature shift is not cosmetic. It reframes the therapeutic goal from 'relieving a plumbing obstruction' to 'modifying a systemic atherothrombotic disease.' This is why the 2023 guideline foregrounds lifelong risk-factor control, lipid lowering, and antithrombotic strategy, and treats revascularization as one tool among many rather than the destination."}]}, {"id": "pathophysiology", "title": "Pathophysiology and the Ischemic Cascade", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Angina is the clinical surface of a supply-demand mismatch. Fixed epicardial stenosis limits maximal coronary flow; when myocardial oxygen demand (heart rate, contractility, wall tension) outstrips a capped supply, subendocardial ischemia develops first because the subendocardium is perfused last and compressed most during systole."}, {"type": "steps", "head": ["The ischemic cascade — the temporal sequence of ischemia"], "items": ["Perfusion heterogeneity (detectable by PET/SPECT/stress CMR perfusion).", "Metabolic derangement (lactate production).", "Diastolic dysfunction (impaired relaxation).", "Systolic dysfunction / regional wall-motion abnormality (stress echo, wall-motion CMR).", "ECG ST-segment changes.", "Angina — the last and least sensitive event in the cascade."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Because angina appears last in the cascade, imaging of perfusion or wall motion detects ischemia before the ECG or the patient does. This is the physiologic justification for stress imaging over exercise ECG alone in patients with an interpretable but low-yield resting tracing."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Demand ischemia is governed by the determinants of myocardial oxygen consumption (MVO2): heart rate, contractility, and wall stress (Laplace: wall stress proportional to pressure times radius, divided by wall thickness). Every antianginal drug works by moving one or more of these levers or by improving supply. Beta-blockers and non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers lower heart rate and contractility; nitrates and dihydropyridines reduce preload/afterload and wall tension and dilate epicardial vessels; ranolazine reduces diastolic wall tension via the late sodium current without touching heart rate or blood pressure."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "In INOCA the lesion is not epicardial. Coronary microvascular dysfunction reflects impaired endothelium-dependent and endothelium-independent microvascular vasodilation (reduced coronary flow reserve, CFR <2.0) or microvascular spasm; vasospastic angina reflects epicardial smooth-muscle hyperreactivity, classically at rest with transient ST-elevation and prompt nitrate response. Distinguishing these endotypes matters because calcium channel blockers are first-line for vasospasm whereas beta-blockers can worsen it by leaving alpha-mediated vasoconstriction unopposed."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Named coronary anatomy and typical stenosis distributions are worth reviewing alongside the ischemic cascade; a labeled coronary tree helps anchor territory-to-symptom reasoning.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia — coronary artery anatomy and CT angiography"}]}, {"id": "presentation-pretest", "title": "Presentation and Pretest Probability", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Classic angina is defined by three features: substernal chest discomfort of characteristic quality and duration, provoked by exertion or emotional stress, and relieved by rest or nitroglycerin. Typical angina meets all three; atypical angina meets two; noncardiac chest pain meets one or none."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Canadian Cardiovascular Society (CCS) Class I", "def": "Angina only with strenuous or prolonged exertion; ordinary activity does not cause angina."}, {"term": "CCS Class II", "def": "Slight limitation of ordinary activity — angina on walking >2 blocks or climbing >1 flight rapidly, in cold, or after meals."}, {"term": "CCS Class III", "def": "Marked limitation — angina walking 1-2 blocks or climbing 1 flight at normal pace."}, {"term": "CCS Class IV", "def": "Inability to perform any activity without angina, or angina at rest."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for anginal quality — 'the 3 P's of ruling it IN and the words that rule it OUT.' Provoked by exertion, Palliated by rest/nitro, Pressure-like and substernal argue for angina. Features that argue against: pleuritic, positional, reproduced by palpation, or fleeting (seconds). Sharp/positional/reproducible pain is the classic 'non-anginal' triad."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The 2023 guideline moved decisively away from the older Diamond-Forrester tables, which systematically overestimated obstructive CAD, especially in women. Contemporary practice uses updated risk models (for example the CAD Consortium / PROMISE-derived scores and the ESC pretest probability tables) that incorporate age, sex, symptom typicality and risk factors, and that classify large groups of stable patients as low pretest probability (<5-15%) in whom deferring testing entirely is reasonable."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Pretest probability band", "Approximate obstructive-CAD likelihood", "Recommended initial approach"], "rows": [["Very low", "<5%", "No routine testing; treat risk factors and reassess."], ["Low", "5-15%", "Testing often deferrable; if pursued, CCTA or exercise ECG is reasonable."], ["Intermediate", "15-50%", "Anatomic (CCTA) or functional stress imaging; testing changes management."], ["High", "50-85%", "Functional imaging to gauge ischemic burden, or CCTA; consider invasive angiography if symptoms refractory."]], "caption": "Pretest probability drives test selection. Testing is most informative in the intermediate-to-high bands where the result meaningfully shifts management."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "A frequent fellow error is testing the very-low and very-high probability patient. In the very-low patient a positive test is more likely false than true (Bayes). In the classic high-probability patient with lifestyle-limiting angina, a non-invasive test rarely changes the plan — proceed toward angiography and revascularization discussion. Test where the pretest probability sits in the informative middle."}]}, {"id": "diagnostic-testing", "title": "Diagnostic Testing: Functional versus Anatomic", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Two complementary strategies exist: anatomic testing (coronary CT angiography) that visualizes plaque and stenosis, and functional testing (stress ECG, stress echo, SPECT/PET myocardial perfusion imaging, stress CMR) that demonstrates inducible ischemia. The 2023 guideline treats CCTA and stress imaging as reasonable first-line options and increasingly favors CCTA in younger patients and those with lower calcium burden, because it also excludes non-obstructive disease that still warrants preventive therapy."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Test", "What it measures", "Best used when", "Key limitation"], "rows": [["Exercise treadmill ECG", "ST-response + functional capacity + symptoms", "Interpretable baseline ECG, able to exercise, lower pretest probability", "Poor sensitivity/specificity; uninterpretable if baseline ST abnormal, paced, LBBB, or on digoxin"], ["Stress echocardiography", "Inducible wall-motion abnormality", "Need imaging, avoid radiation, assess valves/EF simultaneously", "Operator-dependent; poor acoustic windows"], ["SPECT / PET MPI", "Regional perfusion (ischemia + scar); PET adds absolute flow/CFR", "Assess ischemic burden, prior MI, guide revascularization", "Radiation; attenuation artifact (SPECT); balanced ischemia can mask multivessel disease"], ["Stress CMR", "Perfusion + wall motion + viability + scar (LGE)", "Highest spatial resolution; viability and INOCA workup", "Availability; gadolinium; claustrophobia; caution with some devices"], ["Coronary CT angiography (CCTA)", "Plaque burden + luminal stenosis + high-risk plaque features", "Intermediate probability, younger patients, rule-OUT obstructive disease", "Blooming from heavy calcium; needs rate control; contrast/radiation"], ["Invasive coronary angiography +/- FFR/iFR", "Definitive anatomy + lesion-level physiology", "Refractory symptoms, high-risk non-invasive findings, or when revascularization is likely", "Invasive; procedural risk; overcalls significance without physiology"]], "caption": "Match the test to the question. Anatomy rules out disease and finds high-risk substrate; function quantifies ischemic burden and guides whether a lesion is causing the symptoms."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "FFR-CT: a CCTA can be post-processed with computational fluid dynamics to derive a fractional flow reserve value non-invasively. An FFR-CT <=0.80 flags a hemodynamically significant lesion and improves the specificity of CCTA, reducing unnecessary invasive angiograms (PLATFORM, ADVANCE registry)."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Fractional flow reserve (FFR)", "def": "Ratio of maximal hyperemic flow across a lesion to normal; <=0.80 defines a physiologically significant stenosis warranting revascularization (FAME, FAME 2)."}, {"term": "Instantaneous wave-free ratio (iFR)", "def": "Resting pressure ratio during the diastolic wave-free period; <=0.89 is the ischemic threshold. Avoids adenosine (DEFINE-FLAIR, iFR-SWEDEHEART)."}, {"term": "Coronary flow reserve (CFR)", "def": "Ratio of hyperemic to resting flow; <2.0 indicates impaired flow reserve and, when epicardial arteries are normal, points to microvascular dysfunction."}, {"term": "Coronary artery calcium (CAC) score", "def": "Agatston-scored CT quantification of calcified plaque. CAC of 0 confers very low near-term event risk in asymptomatic patients; high CAC reclassifies risk upward and supports intensified prevention."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Balanced ischemia is a classic SPECT trap: in severe three-vessel or left main disease, global hypoperfusion can appear relatively uniform, understating the true burden. Corroborate with functional capacity, transient ischemic dilation, post-stress EF drop, and lung uptake — or move to PET (absolute flow) or anatomic imaging when suspicion is high."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "For the ECG correlates of ischemia and the stress-test ST patterns you will read daily, a curated ECG library is a useful adjunct.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — ischemia and exercise-ECG patterns"}]}, {"id": "risk-stratification", "title": "Risk Stratification", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Once CCD is established, the goal of testing shifts from diagnosis to prognosis: identify the minority whose anatomy or physiology predicts a hard-event benefit from revascularization, and reassure the majority in whom medical therapy is sufficient. High-risk non-invasive findings raise the priority for invasive evaluation."}, {"type": "list", "head": ["High-risk non-invasive markers"], "items": ["Large or multi-territory ischemia (>=10% of myocardium ischemic on MPI, or multiple ischemic segments on stress echo/CMR).", "Stress-induced LV dysfunction: fall in EF, transient ischemic dilation, or a large reversible perfusion defect.", "Exercise limitation with early ischemia (low workload, hypotensive BP response, sustained ventricular arrhythmia).", "Left main or proximal LAD disease, or three-vessel disease on CCTA.", "Reduced resting LV ejection fraction attributable to CAD.", "High coronary artery calcium score with obstructive features."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "ISCHEMIA reframed ischemic burden. Pre-ISCHEMIA, a large ischemic burden was treated almost as a mandate to revascularize. ISCHEMIA showed that even moderate-to-severe ischemia does not, by itself, confer a mortality benefit from routine revascularization. Burden still identifies higher-risk patients, but it no longer automatically triggers the cath lab in the absence of refractory symptoms or the specific anatomic subsets (left main, low EF) that carry independent revascularization benefit."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Two anatomic-prognostic populations sit outside the ISCHEMIA conclusion and retain a survival rationale for revascularization: significant left main disease and ischemic cardiomyopathy with viable myocardium. Left main was deliberately excluded from ISCHEMIA (screened out by the protocol CCTA). The STICH trial and its extended follow-up (STICHES) support CABG plus medical therapy over medical therapy alone in ischemic cardiomyopathy with EF <=35%, with a survival benefit emerging over long-term follow-up."}]}, {"id": "ischemia-framework", "title": "The ISCHEMIA-Era Framework", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "ISCHEMIA (2020) randomized more than 5,000 patients with stable CAD and moderate-to-severe ischemia to an initial invasive strategy (angiography plus revascularization when feasible, on top of medical therapy) versus an initial conservative strategy (optimal medical therapy, with angiography reserved for failure). Left main disease was excluded by blinded CCTA, and patients with recent ACS, EF <35%, or unacceptable angina were excluded."}, {"type": "steps", "head": ["What ISCHEMIA established"], "items": ["No significant reduction in the primary composite of cardiovascular death, MI, resuscitated arrest, or hospitalization for unstable angina/heart failure over a median 3.2 years.", "An early procedural hazard (periprocedural MI) offset by later reduction in spontaneous MI — a crossing of the event curves.", "Durable, clinically meaningful improvement in angina frequency and quality of life with the invasive strategy, greatest in those with frequent baseline angina.", "No mortality benefit from routine revascularization in this stable, non-left-main, preserved-EF population.", "Medical therapy is a legitimate and safe first strategy even with substantial ischemia; revascularization is layered on for symptoms."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The one-line ISCHEMIA takeaway: in stable CAD without left main disease or severe LV dysfunction, revascularize for symptoms and quality of life, not for a presumed mortality benefit. Medical therapy first is not undertreatment — it is the guideline."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "ISCHEMIA sits atop a lineage: COURAGE (2007) first showed PCI added to optimal medical therapy did not reduce death or MI in stable CAD; BARI 2D addressed diabetics; ORBITA (2018), a sham-controlled trial, showed the anti-anginal effect of PCI in single-vessel disease was smaller than open-label experience suggested. Together they anchor the medical-therapy-first paradigm. The counterpoints — where revascularization does change hard outcomes — are left main disease, multivessel disease in diabetics (FREEDOM), and ischemic cardiomyopathy (STICH)."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "When counseling a stable patient who wants 'the blockage fixed,' the honest framing is: revascularization is highly effective for relieving angina and improving quality of life, but in your situation it is not expected to help you live longer or prevent a heart attack more than excellent medical therapy will. That sentence, delivered well, is the practical distillation of a decade of trials."}]}, {"id": "antianginal-therapy", "title": "Antianginal Pharmacotherapy", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Antianginal therapy targets the determinants of myocardial oxygen demand and supply. Beta-blockers are first-line in most patients, especially after MI or with reduced EF. Calcium channel blockers and long-acting nitrates are added or substituted, and ranolazine is a metabolic agent reserved for refractory symptoms. The goal is a resting heart rate of roughly 55-60 bpm and abolition of lifestyle-limiting angina."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Beta-blocker", "Start dose", "Target / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Metoprolol succinate (XL)", "25-50 mg PO daily", "100-200 mg daily", "Decompensated HF, high-grade AV block, severe bradycardia, cocaine-associated chest pain", "HR, BP; aim resting HR 55-60"], ["Metoprolol tartrate", "25 mg PO BID", "50-100 mg BID", "As above", "HR, BP"], ["Bisoprolol", "5 mg PO daily", "10 mg daily", "As above", "HR, BP"], ["Carvedilol", "6.25 mg PO BID", "25 mg BID", "As above; caution in reactive airway disease (nonselective)", "HR, BP; preferred with reduced EF"], ["Atenolol", "25-50 mg PO daily", "50-100 mg daily", "As above; renally cleared, accumulates in CKD", "HR, BP, renal function"]], "caption": "Beta-blockers: mechanism is reduced heart rate and contractility (lower MVO2). Class cautions: never stop abruptly (rebound tachycardia/ischemia); avoid combining with non-dihydropyridine CCBs due to additive bradycardia and AV block; may blunt hypoglycemia awareness."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Calcium channel blocker", "Start dose", "Target / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring / notes"], "rows": [["Amlodipine (DHP)", "2.5-5 mg PO daily", "5-10 mg daily", "Severe aortic stenosis; caution with severe LV dysfunction", "Peripheral edema (dose-dependent); safe to combine with beta-blocker"], ["Felodipine (DHP)", "2.5-5 mg PO daily", "5-10 mg daily", "As above", "Edema, flushing, headache"], ["Diltiazem (non-DHP)", "120-180 mg/day (ER)", "180-360 mg/day", "HFrEF/EF <40%, high-grade AV block, sick sinus, plus beta-blocker", "HR, BP, AV conduction; negative inotrope"], ["Verapamil (non-DHP)", "180 mg/day (ER)", "240-480 mg/day", "HFrEF, AV block, plus beta-blocker", "Constipation; strongest negative inotrope; raises digoxin levels"]], "caption": "Dihydropyridines are vasoselective (afterload/epicardial dilation) and safe with beta-blockers. Non-dihydropyridines lower heart rate and contractility — powerful antianginals but dangerous when stacked on a beta-blocker or used in reduced EF. Non-DHP CCBs are the antianginal of choice when a beta-blocker is contraindicated."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Nitrate / other", "Start dose", "Target / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring / notes"], "rows": [["Sublingual nitroglycerin", "0.3-0.4 mg SL PRN", "Repeat q5min x3, then call EMS", "PDE5 inhibitor within 24h (sildenafil/vardenafil) or 48h (tadalafil); RV infarct; severe AS/HOCM", "Every CCD patient should carry it; teach prophylactic pre-exertion use"], ["Isosorbide mononitrate (ER)", "30 mg PO daily", "60-120 mg daily", "As above", "Requires a 10-14h nitrate-free interval to prevent tolerance"], ["Isosorbide dinitrate", "5-10 mg PO TID", "20-40 mg TID (asymmetric dosing)", "As above", "Headache, hypotension; dose to preserve nitrate-free interval"], ["Ranolazine", "500 mg PO BID", "1000 mg BID", "Hepatic cirrhosis; strong CYP3A inhibitors/inducers; drugs that markedly prolong QT", "Does NOT lower HR or BP; QT prolongation; cap at 500 mg BID with diltiazem/verapamil; nausea, dizziness, constipation"]], "caption": "Nitrates reduce preload and wall tension and dilate epicardial/collateral vessels; tolerance mandates a daily nitrate-free interval. Ranolazine inhibits the late inward sodium current, reducing calcium overload and diastolic wall tension — uniquely hemodynamically neutral, ideal when heart rate and blood pressure are already low."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "The nitrate-PDE5 interaction is potentially fatal: co-administration causes precipitous, refractory hypotension. Always ask about sildenafil/vardenafil (within 24h) and tadalafil (within 48h) before giving any nitrate, including in the emergency setting. In suspected RV/inferior infarction, nitrates can drop a preload-dependent ventricle into shock — obtain right-sided leads."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for a hemodynamically fragile patient with angina — reach for the drug that 'does not touch the numbers': ranolazine lowers neither heart rate nor blood pressure, so it is the add-on of choice when the patient is already bradycardic or hypotensive on a beta-blocker and CCB but still has angina."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 3, "text": "Ivabradine, a selective If (funny current) sinoatrial node inhibitor, lowers heart rate without affecting contractility or blood pressure and is an option for angina in sinus rhythm when beta-blockers are insufficient or not tolerated; it requires sinus rhythm and a resting heart rate above roughly 70 bpm to be useful. Nicorandil and trimetazidine are additional antianginals available outside the United States. For vasospastic angina, calcium channel blockers (often long-acting, high-dose) plus long-acting nitrates are the cornerstone, and beta-blockers — particularly nonselective ones — should generally be avoided because unopposed alpha tone can worsen spasm."}]}, {"id": "antithrombotic", "title": "Antiplatelet and Antithrombotic Therapy", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Every patient with CCD needs an antithrombotic backbone. For stable CCD without recent stenting, low-dose aspirin monotherapy is standard. Dual antiplatelet therapy (DAPT) applies for a defined period after PCI, and its duration is individualized against bleeding risk. Selected high-ischemic-risk, low-bleeding-risk patients benefit from adding low-dose rivaroxaban (the vascular-protection dose) to aspirin."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Oral agent", "Mechanism", "Loading dose", "Maintenance", "Key notes / contraindications"], "rows": [["Aspirin", "Irreversible COX-1 / thromboxane A2 inhibition", "162-325 mg (if not already on it)", "75-100 mg (81 mg US) daily", "Lifelong in established CCD; GI bleeding risk; add PPI if high GI risk"], ["Clopidogrel", "Irreversible P2Y12 (prodrug, CYP2C19-activated)", "300-600 mg", "75 mg daily", "CYP2C19 loss-of-function reduces efficacy; preferred P2Y12 for stable elective PCI and when combined with oral anticoagulation"], ["Ticagrelor", "Reversible P2Y12 (direct-acting)", "180 mg", "90 mg BID (60 mg BID for extended post-MI therapy)", "Dyspnea, ventricular pauses; avoid with high maintenance aspirin (>100 mg); no CYP activation needed"], ["Prasugrel", "Irreversible P2Y12 (prodrug, potent)", "60 mg", "10 mg daily (5 mg if <60 kg or >=75 yr)", "Contraindicated with prior stroke/TIA; generally avoid at age >=75; most potent oral, highest bleeding"], ["Rivaroxaban (vascular dose)", "Direct factor Xa inhibitor", "n/a", "2.5 mg BID + aspirin 81 mg daily", "COMPASS regimen for high-risk stable CAD/PAD; reduces MACE at a cost of major bleeding"]], "caption": "P2Y12 selection: clopidogrel for most stable elective PCI; ticagrelor or prasugrel for higher ischemic risk (typically ACS-related). Prasugrel is contraindicated after stroke/TIA. The COMPASS low-dose rivaroxaban-plus-aspirin strategy targets atherothrombotic event reduction in selected patients who tolerate the bleeding trade-off."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for prasugrel exclusions — 'PRASUGREL: PRior stroke, Age 75+, GREatly increased bleeding, Light weight (<60 kg).' In those groups avoid it or reduce the dose; reach for clopidogrel or ticagrelor instead."}, {"type": "p", "text": "Cangrelor is the intravenous P2Y12 inhibitor and deserves specific command because it fills a gap the oral agents cannot: it produces near-complete, immediate platelet inhibition that is fully reversible within an hour of stopping. It is a direct-acting (non-prodrug) reversible antagonist with an ultra-short plasma half-life of roughly 3-6 minutes; platelet function returns to normal about 60 minutes after the infusion ends."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Cangrelor — mechanism", "def": "Intravenous, direct-acting, reversible P2Y12 receptor antagonist. No hepatic activation required, so onset is within minutes — unlike oral prodrugs that take hours to achieve full effect, particularly in patients with impaired absorption."}, {"term": "Cangrelor — the scenario it solves", "def": "(1) A P2Y12-naive patient going for PCI who needs immediate, reliable platelet inhibition on the table; and (2) bridging antiplatelet effect when oral agents cannot be absorbed or given — the NPO patient, intubated/sedated patient, active vomiting, malabsorption, or a patient whose oral P2Y12 must be held before urgent surgery but who needs ongoing inhibition until close to the operating room."}, {"term": "Cangrelor — evidence", "def": "CHAMPION PHOENIX randomized cangrelor versus clopidogrel at the time of PCI and reduced periprocedural ischemic events (including stent thrombosis) without a significant increase in severe bleeding. The BRIDGE trial studied a lower-dose cangrelor infusion for preoperative bridging in patients who required thienopyridine discontinuation before cardiac surgery."}]}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Parameter", "Cangrelor detail"], "rows": [["PCI bolus", "30 mcg/kg IV bolus immediately before PCI"], ["PCI infusion", "4 mcg/kg/min IV, continued for at least 2 hours OR the duration of the PCI, whichever is longer"], ["Surgical bridging (off-label, BRIDGE)", "Lower-dose infusion of 0.75 mcg/kg/min WITHOUT a bolus, started after oral P2Y12 is stopped and continued until roughly 1-6 hours before surgery"], ["Onset / offset", "Full platelet inhibition within ~2 minutes; recovery of platelet function within ~60 minutes of stopping"], ["Transition to ticagrelor", "May be given at any time during or at the end of the infusion (ticagrelor binds a non-competing site, so no interference)"], ["Transition to clopidogrel or prasugrel", "Give 600 mg clopidogrel (or 60 mg prasugrel) immediately AFTER the infusion is stopped, never during — cangrelor occupies the receptor and prevents the active metabolites from binding, so dosing during the infusion is wasted"], ["Contraindications", "Significant active bleeding; hypersensitivity to cangrelor"], ["Monitoring / reversal", "Monitor for bleeding; no specific antidote needed given the ~1-hour offset; not removed by dialysis"]], "caption": "Cangrelor practical card. Note the two distinct regimens: the high-dose PCI regimen (30 mcg/kg bolus + 4 mcg/kg/min) versus the lower BRIDGE surgical-bridging infusion (0.75 mcg/kg/min, no bolus). The transition rule is the single highest-yield teaching point: ticagrelor can be co-administered, but clopidogrel and prasugrel must be given only after the infusion ends."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Do not load clopidogrel or prasugrel during a cangrelor infusion. Cangrelor competitively occupies the P2Y12 receptor, so the active metabolites of these irreversible prodrugs have nowhere to bind and are cleared before they can act, leaving the patient unprotected when the infusion stops. Ticagrelor is the exception and may be given during the infusion."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Frame cangrelor as the 'bridge with a short leash': you can turn platelet inhibition on hard and immediately and turn it off within an hour. That makes it ideal for the P2Y12-naive patient on the table and for the NPO/malabsorbing patient who still needs coverage. Its short offset is also the pharmacologic reason it can bridge a patient who must stop oral P2Y12 before urgent surgery while keeping ischemic protection until close to the operating room — recognizing that the preoperative bridging use (BRIDGE-style, 0.75 mcg/kg/min) is off-label."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "DAPT duration in CCD is a bleeding-versus-ischemia negotiation. After elective PCI for stable disease, roughly 6 months of DAPT is standard, shortened to 1-3 months in high-bleeding-risk patients (guided by tools such as PRECISE-DAPT and the ARC-HBR criteria) and potentially extended in selected high-ischemic-risk patients. When a CCD patient also needs oral anticoagulation (for example atrial fibrillation), the contemporary default is to minimize triple therapy — a short peri-PCI period of triple therapy followed by an anticoagulant plus a single antiplatelet (usually clopidogrel), transitioning to anticoagulant monotherapy by around 12 months (WOEST, PIONEER AF-PCI, AUGUSTUS)."}]}, {"id": "secondary-prevention", "title": "Lipid, Metabolic, and Secondary Prevention", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The disease-modifying core of CCD care is aggressive risk-factor control. High-intensity statin therapy is mandatory in all patients who tolerate it, with add-on agents driven to guideline LDL-C targets. Metabolic therapies with proven cardiovascular benefit (SGLT2 inhibitors, GLP-1 receptor agonists) and the antithrombotic strategies above complete the regimen."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Lipid agent", "Mechanism", "Dose", "Effect / role", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Atorvastatin / rosuvastatin", "HMG-CoA reductase inhibition", "Atorvastatin 40-80 mg; rosuvastatin 20-40 mg", "High-intensity: >=50% LDL-C reduction; foundational in all CCD", "Baseline lipids/LFTs; myalgia; check for drug interactions"], ["Ezetimibe", "Intestinal NPC1L1 cholesterol-absorption inhibition", "10 mg daily", "Adds ~15-25% LDL-C reduction; first add-on (IMPROVE-IT)", "Generally well tolerated"], ["Evolocumab / alirocumab (PCSK9 mAb)", "PCSK9 inhibition, upregulates LDL receptors", "Evolocumab 140 mg SC q2wk or 420 mg monthly", "Additional ~50-60% LDL-C reduction; MACE benefit (FOURIER, ODYSSEY OUTCOMES)", "Injection-site reactions"], ["Inclisiran", "siRNA against PCSK9", "284 mg SC at 0 and 3 months, then q6 months", "Durable LDL-C lowering with twice-yearly dosing", "Injection-site reactions"], ["Bempedoic acid", "ATP-citrate lyase inhibition (liver-selective)", "180 mg daily", "Option for statin-intolerant; MACE benefit (CLEAR Outcomes)", "Uric acid, tendon effects"], ["Icosapent ethyl", "Purified EPA; pleiotropic anti-atherothrombotic", "2 g PO BID (4 g/day)", "MACE reduction in treated patients with elevated triglycerides (REDUCE-IT)", "Atrial fibrillation risk, bleeding"]], "caption": "Lipid ladder: high-intensity statin first, then ezetimibe, then a PCSK9-directed agent (monoclonal or inclisiran) to reach targets. Contemporary practice targets LDL-C well under 70 mg/dL, and under 55 mg/dL in very-high-risk patients."}, {"type": "list", "head": ["Beyond lipids — the disease-modifying bundle"], "items": ["SGLT2 inhibitors (empagliflozin, dapagliflozin): cardiovascular and heart-failure benefit; indicated broadly in CCD with diabetes, heart failure, or CKD independent of glucose control.", "GLP-1 receptor agonists (semaglutide, liraglutide, dulaglutide): MACE reduction in diabetes with established cardiovascular disease and increasingly for weight/cardiometabolic risk.", "ACE inhibitor or ARB: indicated with hypertension, diabetes, CKD, or reduced EF; reasonable in higher-risk CCD (HOPE, EUROPA).", "Blood pressure to guideline target (generally <130/80 mmHg).", "Complete smoking cessation, cardiac rehabilitation, Mediterranean-style diet, and structured exercise.", "Influenza and other appropriate vaccinations — reduce cardiovascular events during acute infection."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the CCD secondary-prevention bundle — 'ABCDE': Antiplatelet + Antianginal, Beta-blocker + Blood pressure, Cholesterol + Cigarettes (statin + cessation), Diet + Diabetes (SGLT2/GLP-1), Exercise + Education (cardiac rehab). Running the alphabet at every visit prevents omission of a proven therapy."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The largest attributable mortality gains in CCD come not from the cath lab but from the medication list and lifestyle: high-intensity statin, LDL-C driven to target, blood-pressure control, smoking cessation, and cardiac rehabilitation. A fellow who optimizes these relentlessly outperforms one who focuses on angiography."}]}, {"id": "revascularization", "title": "Revascularization Decisions: PCI versus CABG", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "When revascularization is indicated — for refractory symptoms despite optimal medical therapy, or for a high-risk anatomic substrate — the choice between PCI and CABG turns on anatomic complexity, diabetic status, and ventricular function. The Heart Team, combining interventional cardiology, cardiac surgery, and the patient, is the guideline-endorsed vehicle for complex decisions."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "SYNTAX score", "def": "An angiographic complexity score summing lesion characteristics across the coronary tree. Low <=22, intermediate 23-32, high >=33. Higher scores predict worse PCI outcomes and favor CABG for left main and multivessel disease."}, {"term": "Complete versus incomplete revascularization", "def": "CABG more readily achieves complete revascularization of diffuse/complex disease; residual ischemia after incomplete PCI predicts recurrent events."}, {"term": "Arterial grafting", "def": "The left internal mammary artery to the LAD provides the durable survival advantage of CABG; multi-arterial grafting extends graft longevity."}]}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Anatomic scenario", "Favored strategy", "Key trial / rationale"], "rows": [["Single/two-vessel non-LAD, preserved EF", "PCI (or medical therapy first)", "ISCHEMIA / COURAGE — revascularize for symptoms"], ["Left main, low-intermediate SYNTAX", "PCI reasonable OR CABG", "EXCEL, NOBLE — comparable in lower-complexity left main; individualize"], ["Left main, high SYNTAX", "CABG", "Higher complexity favors surgical durability"], ["Multivessel + diabetes", "CABG", "FREEDOM — CABG reduced death/MI versus PCI in diabetics with multivessel disease"], ["Multivessel, high SYNTAX, non-diabetic", "CABG", "SYNTAX — CABG superior at higher anatomic complexity"], ["Ischemic cardiomyopathy, EF <=35%, viable myocardium", "CABG + medical therapy", "STICH / STICHES — long-term survival benefit"]], "caption": "The decisive branch points are diabetes plus multivessel disease (FREEDOM favors CABG) and anatomic complexity (rising SYNTAX favors CABG). Preserved-EF single/two-vessel disease is the ISCHEMIA/COURAGE domain where medical therapy leads and PCI relieves symptoms."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — 'diabetics do better with a Detour': in the diabetic with multivessel disease, the FREEDOM trial favors the surgical bypass (CABG) over stents. Pair it with 'the higher the SYNTAX, the stronger the Scalpel.'"}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Lesion-level physiology should gate PCI. In stable multivessel disease, deferring PCI on lesions with FFR >0.80 (or iFR >0.89) is safe and reduces unnecessary stenting; FAME established FFR-guided PCI, and FAME 2 showed FFR-guided PCI plus medical therapy reduced urgent revascularization versus medical therapy alone in functionally significant lesions. The physiologic threshold, not the angiographic eyeball, should decide whether a moderate lesion is treated."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Do not stent an angiographically moderate (40-70%) lesion on visual estimate alone in stable disease. Ocular stenosis assessment is unreliable and drives overtreatment. Interrogate physiology (FFR/iFR) or ischemic burden before committing to a stent, and always ensure the patient is on optimal medical therapy first."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "Reviewing representative angiographic views (left and right coronary systems, left main bifurcation anatomy) alongside SYNTAX concepts reinforces complexity assessment.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia — coronary angiography and CT"}]}, {"id": "inoca-refractory", "title": "INOCA, Vasospasm, and Refractory Angina", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "A substantial minority of patients — disproportionately women — have angina and objective ischemia without an obstructive epicardial stenosis. Dismissing these patients as 'clean coronaries' misses treatable microvascular and vasospastic disease that carries genuine prognostic and quality-of-life weight."}, {"type": "steps", "head": ["Structured INOCA/ANOCA workup"], "items": ["Confirm ischemia objectively (stress imaging, or invasive physiology).", "Exclude obstructive epicardial disease (CCTA or angiography).", "Invasive coronary function testing: measure coronary flow reserve (CFR) and index of microcirculatory resistance (IMR) for microvascular dysfunction.", "Provocation testing (acetylcholine) to unmask epicardial or microvascular spasm.", "Assign the endotype — microvascular, vasospastic, or mixed — and treat accordingly (CorMicA trial approach)."]}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Endotype", "Signature", "Preferred therapy"], "rows": [["Microvascular dysfunction", "Low CFR (<2.0) / high IMR; exertional angina", "Beta-blockers, ACE inhibitors, statins; ranolazine for symptoms"], ["Vasospastic (Prinzmetal)", "Rest angina, transient ST-elevation, acetylcholine-provoked spasm", "Calcium channel blockers (high-dose, long-acting) + long-acting nitrates; AVOID nonselective beta-blockers"], ["Mixed", "Features of both", "Individualized combination guided by dominant mechanism"]], "caption": "Endotyping changes drug choice. The critical safety point: beta-blockers can aggravate coronary vasospasm, so in confirmed vasospastic angina, calcium channel blockers and nitrates lead."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Refractory angina — disabling symptoms despite optimal medical therapy and when further revascularization is not feasible or has been exhausted — is managed with intensified antianginal layering (adding ranolazine, optimizing nitrate scheduling, considering ivabradine in sinus tachycardia), cardiac rehabilitation, treatment of comorbid depression and anxiety, and referral to specialized programs. Enhanced external counterpulsation and, at select centers, the coronary sinus reducer device are options for the truly refractory patient."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "In a woman with classic exertional angina, positive stress imaging, and non-obstructive coronaries at angiography, resist the urge to stop at 'non-cardiac.' Proceed to coronary function testing when available — CorMicA showed that a stratified medical-therapy approach guided by invasive endotyping improves angina and quality of life."}]}, {"id": "clinical-algorithm", "title": "Putting It Together: A Clinical Algorithm", "body": [{"type": "steps", "head": ["From stable chest pain to a management plan"], "items": ["Characterize symptoms (typicality, CCS class) and estimate pretest probability with a contemporary model.", "Very-low probability: no testing; address risk factors. Intermediate-high: select CCTA (anatomy/rule-out) or stress imaging (ischemic burden).", "Establish optimal medical therapy in EVERY patient: high-intensity statin to LDL target, aspirin, beta-blocker/antianginal, blood-pressure and glucose control, lifestyle and cardiac rehab.", "Assess ischemic burden and high-risk markers; identify left main, multivessel-plus-diabetes, or low-EF substrates that carry independent revascularization benefit.", "If symptoms are controlled and no high-risk substrate: continue and intensify medical therapy (the ISCHEMIA conservative arm).", "If angina is refractory despite optimal medical therapy, or a high-risk substrate is present: angiography with lesion-level physiology and a Heart Team decision on PCI versus CABG.", "For non-obstructive disease with ischemia: pursue INOCA endotyping and targeted therapy rather than reassurance alone."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The whole module in one sentence: medical therapy first for everyone, test where it changes management, and reserve the cath lab for refractory symptoms or the anatomic subsets (left main, diabetic multivessel disease, low-EF ischemic cardiomyopathy) where revascularization genuinely changes outcomes."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "On rounds, be the one who can recite the antianginal doses and the cangrelor transition rule from memory, name the trial behind each decision (ISCHEMIA, COURAGE, FREEDOM, EXCEL, STICH, FAME, CHAMPION PHOENIX, COMPASS), and still lead with 'is this patient on maximal medical therapy?' That combination — pharmacologic precision plus trial-anchored restraint — is what fellowship-level CCD care looks like."}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 61-year-old man with hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and stable CCS class II exertional angina is on maximally tolerated metoprolol succinate (resting HR 56) and amlodipine, plus high-intensity atorvastatin and aspirin. He still has angina climbing two flights of stairs but is otherwise active. Stress CMR shows moderate inferolateral ischemia (~8% of myocardium) without left main or proximal LAD disease; EF is 58%. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Refer for immediate invasive coronary angiography with intent to revascularize to reduce his risk of myocardial infarction and death"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Add ranolazine 500 mg twice daily and reinforce optimal medical therapy, reserving angiography for refractory symptoms"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Stop the beta-blocker and start high-dose isosorbide mononitrate as monotherapy"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Proceed directly to CABG given multiterritory ischemia"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Discontinue aspirin and start low-dose rivaroxaban monotherapy"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is a classic ISCHEMIA-arm patient: stable, preserved EF, no left main or proximal LAD disease, moderate ischemia. ISCHEMIA showed no mortality or MI benefit from routine revascularization over optimal medical therapy in this population, though revascularization improves angina. Because he still has symptoms on a beta-blocker and calcium channel blocker but a low heart rate and controlled blood pressure, ranolazine — which lowers neither heart rate nor blood pressure — is the ideal next antianginal, while continuing to optimize medical therapy. Angiography is appropriate only if symptoms become refractory. Stopping the beta-blocker (C) removes a prognostically useful agent; CABG (D) is not indicated for this substrate; rivaroxaban monotherapy (E) is not the COMPASS regimen, which adds low-dose rivaroxaban to aspirin rather than replacing it."}, {"stem": "A 58-year-old woman is undergoing PCI of the RCA for stable angina refractory to medical therapy. She is P2Y12-naive because her oral clopidogrel was held and she has been vomiting, so reliable oral absorption cannot be assured on the table. The operator elects intravenous cangrelor. Which statement about her antithrombotic management is correct?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Load oral clopidogrel 600 mg during the cangrelor infusion so platelet inhibition is seamless when the infusion stops"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Give cangrelor 30 mcg/kg IV bolus then 4 mcg/kg/min infusion for at least 2 hours or the duration of PCI, and load clopidogrel or prasugrel only after the infusion ends"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Cangrelor requires 6 hours to reach full platelet inhibition, so pretreatment the night before is essential"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Because cangrelor is irreversible, platelet function will not recover for 5-7 days after stopping the infusion"}, {"key": "E", "text": "A specific reversal agent must be immediately available before starting the cangrelor infusion"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Cangrelor is a direct-acting, reversible intravenous P2Y12 antagonist dosed for PCI as a 30 mcg/kg bolus followed by a 4 mcg/kg/min infusion continued for at least 2 hours or the duration of PCI, whichever is longer. Its onset is within minutes and platelet function recovers within about an hour of stopping — ideal for a P2Y12-naive patient who cannot reliably absorb oral agents. Because cangrelor occupies the receptor, the active metabolites of clopidogrel and prasugrel cannot bind if loaded during the infusion, so these must be given only after the infusion ends (A is dangerous and wrong). Ticagrelor is the exception and may be given during the infusion. Cangrelor is fast, not slow (C), reversible not irreversible (D), and its short half-life obviates the need for a reversal agent (E)."}, {"stem": "A 55-year-old man with type 2 diabetes presents with lifestyle-limiting angina despite optimal medical therapy. Angiography reveals significant three-vessel disease with a SYNTAX score of 34, EF 50%, and no left main involvement. He is an acceptable surgical candidate. Which revascularization strategy is best supported by the evidence?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Multivessel PCI with drug-eluting stents"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Coronary artery bypass grafting"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Continued medical therapy alone with no revascularization"}, {"key": "D", "text": "PCI of the single most stenotic vessel only"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Enhanced external counterpulsation as definitive therapy"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "In diabetics with multivessel coronary disease, the FREEDOM trial demonstrated that CABG reduced the composite of death and myocardial infarction compared with multivessel PCI. This patient has both diagnostic features that favor surgery — diabetes with multivessel disease (FREEDOM) and high anatomic complexity (SYNTAX 34, where the SYNTAX trial favored CABG). Multivessel or single-vessel PCI (A, D) is inferior here; medical therapy alone (C) leaves refractory symptoms unaddressed and forgoes the survival advantage in this high-risk substrate; EECP (E) is reserved for refractory angina when revascularization is not feasible, which is not the case."}, {"stem": "A 47-year-old woman has recurrent rest chest pain, often in the early morning, with transient inferior ST-elevation captured on a prior tracing that resolved with sublingual nitroglycerin. Coronary angiography shows no obstructive epicardial disease, and acetylcholine provocation reproduces her symptoms with focal epicardial spasm. Which therapy is most appropriate, and which should be avoided?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Start a long-acting calcium channel blocker and nitrate; avoid nonselective beta-blockers"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Start a nonselective beta-blocker as first-line therapy"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Proceed to PCI of the spastic segment with a drug-eluting stent"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Reassure her that non-obstructive coronaries mean a benign, untreatable condition"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Begin dual antiplatelet therapy with prasugrel and aspirin indefinitely"}], "correct": "A", "explanation": "This is vasospastic (Prinzmetal) angina: rest pain, transient ST-elevation, prompt nitrate response, and acetylcholine-provoked epicardial spasm without obstructive disease. Calcium channel blockers (often high-dose, long-acting) combined with long-acting nitrates are the cornerstone of therapy. Nonselective beta-blockers should be avoided because unopposed alpha-adrenergic tone can worsen coronary spasm (B). There is no fixed lesion to stent (C); the condition is real and treatable, not benign and untreatable (D); and potent DAPT with prasugrel (E) is not indicated for vasospasm and carries unnecessary bleeding risk."}, {"stem": "During elective evaluation of a 63-year-old man with atypical chest pain and intermediate pretest probability, coronary CT angiography shows a moderate (50-60%) stenosis in the mid-LAD. He is on a statin and aspirin. Which approach best reflects contemporary, physiology-guided management of this lesion?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Stent the lesion based on the angiographic appearance because any 50-60% stenosis warrants revascularization"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Assess the lesion physiologically (FFR-CT, or invasive FFR/iFR) and defer revascularization if it is not hemodynamically significant, while optimizing medical therapy"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Refer for CABG given LAD involvement regardless of physiology"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Stop the statin because the stenosis is only moderate"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Repeat CCTA in one week to see if the lesion has progressed"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Angiographic estimation of moderate (40-70%) lesions is unreliable and drives overtreatment. Physiologic assessment — FFR-CT non-invasively, or invasive FFR (ischemic threshold <=0.80) or iFR (<=0.89) — determines whether the lesion is hemodynamically significant. FAME and FAME 2 support deferring PCI on lesions above these thresholds and treating only functionally significant stenoses, always on a foundation of optimal medical therapy. Reflexive stenting (A) or CABG (C) on visual grounds is inappropriate; stopping the statin (D) is harmful; and repeating imaging in a week (E) provides no useful information."}], "takeaways": ["Chronic coronary disease is a lifelong systemic atherothrombotic process, not a fixable plumbing problem; optimal medical therapy is the foundation for every patient and revascularization is layered on for refractory symptoms or high-risk anatomy.", "ISCHEMIA (and before it COURAGE, ORBITA, BARI 2D) established that routine revascularization does not reduce death or MI over optimal medical therapy in stable, non-left-main, preserved-EF disease, though it does relieve angina — so revascularize for symptoms and quality of life, not for a presumed mortality benefit.", "The revascularization survival exceptions are left main disease, multivessel disease with diabetes (FREEDOM favors CABG), rising anatomic complexity (higher SYNTAX favors CABG), and ischemic cardiomyopathy with viable myocardium (STICH).", "Know the antianginal doses cold: beta-blocker first (target resting HR 55-60), add a dihydropyridine or long-acting nitrate, and use ranolazine (500-1000 mg BID) as the hemodynamically neutral add-on when heart rate and blood pressure are already low; never stack a non-dihydropyridine CCB on a beta-blocker.", "Cangrelor is the intravenous, direct-acting, reversible P2Y12 inhibitor for the P2Y12-naive patient on the table or the patient who cannot absorb oral agents: PCI dosing is a 30 mcg/kg bolus then 4 mcg/kg/min for at least 2 hours or the PCI duration; ticagrelor may be given during the infusion, but clopidogrel and prasugrel must be loaded only after the infusion ends because cangrelor blocks their active metabolites from binding.", "The largest mortality gains in CCD come from the medication list and lifestyle, captured by the ABCDE bundle: Antiplatelet/Antianginal, Beta-blocker/Blood pressure, Cholesterol (high-intensity statin to target, add ezetimibe then PCSK9)/Cigarettes, Diet/Diabetes (SGLT2, GLP-1), and Exercise/Education (cardiac rehab).", "Match the test to the question and to pretest probability: test in the informative intermediate-to-high range, use CCTA (with FFR-CT) to rule out obstructive disease and find high-risk substrate, use stress imaging to quantify ischemic burden, and interrogate moderate lesions with FFR (<=0.80) or iFR (<=0.89) before stenting."], "references": ["2023 AHA/ACC/ACCP/ASPC/NLA/PCNA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Chronic Coronary Disease", "2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization", "2024 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Chronic Coronary Syndromes", "ISCHEMIA and ISCHEMIA-EXTEND trials (initial invasive vs conservative strategy in stable ischemic heart disease)", "Landmark revascularization trials: COURAGE, ORBITA, BARI 2D, FREEDOM, SYNTAX, EXCEL, NOBLE, STICH/STICHES", "Coronary physiology and antithrombotic trials: FAME, FAME 2, DEFINE-FLAIR, iFR-SWEDEHEART, CHAMPION PHOENIX (cangrelor), BRIDGE (cangrelor bridging), COMPASS (low-dose rivaroxaban)", "Secondary-prevention outcome trials: IMPROVE-IT, FOURIER, ODYSSEY OUTCOMES, CLEAR Outcomes, REDUCE-IT, EMPA-REG OUTCOME", "CorMicA trial (stratified medical therapy for INOCA guided by invasive coronary function testing)"], "guidelines": [{"society": "AHA/ACC", "text": "All patients with chronic coronary disease who tolerate it should receive high-intensity statin therapy, with addition of ezetimibe and a PCSK9-directed agent as needed to achieve guideline LDL-C targets.", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC", "text": "In patients with CCD, cardiac rehabilitation, smoking cessation, blood-pressure control, and a heart-healthy diet are recommended to reduce cardiovascular events and improve quality of life.", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC", "text": "Beta-blockers, calcium channel blockers, and long-acting nitrates are recommended as antianginal therapy, with ranolazine as an option for persistent angina; therapy should be optimized before considering revascularization for symptom relief.", "cor": "I", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC", "text": "In patients with diabetes and multivessel coronary disease appropriate for surgery, CABG is recommended in preference to PCI to reduce death and recurrent myocardial infarction.", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2021"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC", "text": "In stable patients with intermediate-complexity coronary lesions, use of fractional flow reserve or instantaneous wave-free ratio to guide the decision to revascularize is recommended over angiographic assessment alone.", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2021"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC", "text": "In selected patients with CCD at high ischemic and low bleeding risk, addition of low-dose rivaroxaban to aspirin can be beneficial to reduce major adverse cardiovascular events.", "cor": "IIa", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "ESC", "text": "In patients with suspected chronic coronary syndrome and low-to-intermediate pretest probability, coronary CT angiography is recommended as the initial test to establish the diagnosis and exclude obstructive disease.", "cor": "I", "year": "2024"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA/SCAI", "text": "Cangrelor may be reasonable in P2Y12-inhibitor-naive patients undergoing PCI to reduce periprocedural ischemic events, with attention to correct timing of transition to an oral P2Y12 inhibitor.", "cor": "IIb", "year": "2021"}]};
